Of the things which are in our power, some are morally neutral and indifferent, having in them, as to their natures, nothing ot* moral good or evil 3 as, to go to the market·place, to write a letter. These are matters of Free Will, but not, of their own nature, matters of Conscience. I say, of their own nature, for, in virtue of some accessory circumstance, as the occasioning scandal, or the like, they may become matters of Conscience. Other acts are of their own nature good or evi13 as to worship God, to honour our parents, to return what is entrusted to us3 to keep saith or to break faith; to oppress the poor; all in short that is matter of praise or blame 3 meritorious or demeritorious, as the schoolmen speak3 and about this last class properly is Oonscience employed.
